availability.p: For internal use by the Faclair na Gàidhlig/DASG projects

note.p: A 16th-century medical and astological manuscript, mostly written by members of the Beaton medical family.

msContents.summary: This transcription file currently includes: (1) 11 charms from the first half of the manuscript; (2) Excerpts from the Latin translation of Averroes's Colliget (?), with Gaelic translation; (3) A letter from Lachlan Mór MacLean of Duart to his physician; (4) A tract on anatomy.

note.p: The "g" has a suspension stoke over it, but no expansion is needed.
An insertion mark appears here but nothing is now visible interlinearly or in the margins for insertion nor is any material obviously marked up for exchange or substitution within the main text.

There are dots underneath "in macluic", which are possibly there to show that it is being cancelled. However, they are faint and not clearly distinguishable from other irregular marks on the page elsewhere.

p.note: HDSG MSS Slip 0002385 expands this word as ebar ("ivory"), which is understood to have the sense of "charm"; however, as epaid is well-attested as a word with the same sense, including elsewhere in this manuscript, this seems an unnecessary stretch.

note.p: Black (0061076) suggests tentatively that this is a particular type of toothache but, in the absence of further evidence for this, it seems more straightforward as reading it as the word "tooth" (dét) itself.

note.p: A suspenion stroke is over "p" but no expansion is needed to complete the word.

What is actually happened here is as follows. Hand12 wrote "corp", then Hand14 scored out "cor", lenited "p", and added "onc" above the line. Only one "p" thus appears on the page, but there was no way of encoding this accurately while also retaining both words.
